    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Translator profile importance weights 0-10",
    "content": "1: 10 -- Non-negotiable. The source texts are in Chinese and the target is English.\n2: 9 -- The essays are philosophy, not literature. A literary translator without philosophical training will flatten the arguments.\n3: 8 -- The cat passage, the 梦境 section, the 诗意 concept all require literary feel. But this is secondary to philosophical precision.\n4: 7 -- Essential for K1策略 and 范畴论与境. Lower than one might expect because a philosophically trained translator can consult our experts for the math; they cannot easily consult us for prose quality.\n5: 9 -- This collection's range is extreme: memes, RPG references, classical Chinese quotations, LaTeX formalism, and poetic philosophical prose all coexist. A translator who can only do one register will fail.\n6: 7 -- Important for 后形而上学 and the 道德仁义礼 passage. But the author deliberately departs from standard renderings (coining 现象礼 etc.), so over-familiarity with conventions could actually be a liability if the translator defaults to Legge/Waley where the author intends something different.\n7: 8 -- Load-bearing for the Bob sequence, the Sisyphus-to-cat descent, and the 道德仁义礼 reversal. Without this awareness, the translator may reorganize or condense passages that must remain structurally intact.\n8: 6 -- Useful background but the essays do not heavily deploy standard existentialist/phenomenological terminology. The author tends to coin rather than borrow.\n9: 4 -- Only relevant for occasional resonances. The essays do not engage Buddhist technical vocabulary substantively. Our buddhism-expert can advise on the few relevant points.\n10: 6 -- The Kantian resonances are structural rather than terminological. The author does not use Kantian terms; the parallel is conceptual. The kantian-expert's report is sufficient guidance.\n11: 5 -- Relevant mainly for K1策略's language-knowledge sections. The author does not use Brandom's or Anscombe's terminology, but a translator familiar with this register would better handle the language-as-knowledge-framework passages. Consultable rather than essential."
  }
}
